{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17658329","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17658329"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:46:23+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:46:23+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20727"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20727","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20727"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0.65,0,0,0.35]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13603"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"95401"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13603","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13603"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20727"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78277"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"11578"},{"type":"tags","id":"11742"},{"type":"tags","id":"12604"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"32708"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32709"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"95401","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/95401"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the inheritance pattern and genetic characteristics of mitochondria?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["X-linked inheritance with nuclear DNA encoding all mitochondrial proteins","Maternal inheritance with mitochondrial DNA encoding some oxidative phosphorylation proteins","Biparental inheritance with equal contributions from both parents","Paternal inheritance with mitochondrial DNA encoding respiratory chain proteins","Maternal inheritance with mitochondrial DNA encoding all mitochondrial proteins"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer is \u003Cstrong\u003Ematernal inheritance with mitochondrial DNA encoding some oxidative phosphorylation proteins\u003C/strong\u003E. Mitochondria are primarily maternally inherited because the ovum contributes the vast majority of cytoplasmic organelles to the fertilized zygote. Mitochondrial DNA encodes approximately 1% of total cellular protein and about 20% of the proteins involved in oxidative phosphorylation. The remaining mitochondrial proteins are encoded by nuclear DNA.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EX-linked inheritance with nuclear DNA encoding all mitochondrial proteins\u003C/strong\u003E - While nuclear DNA does encode most mitochondrial proteins, mitochondrial inheritance is maternal, not X-linked. Additionally, mitochondrial DNA encodes some proteins (not all proteins are encoded by nuclear DNA).\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBiparental inheritance with equal contributions from both parents\u003C/strong\u003E - Mitochondria are almost exclusively maternally inherited, not biparentally.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPaternal inheritance with mitochondrial DNA encoding respiratory chain proteins\u003C/strong\u003E - Mitochondria are maternally inherited, not paternally inherited.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMaternal inheritance with mitochondrial DNA encoding all mitochondrial proteins\u003C/strong\u003E - While mitochondria are maternally inherited, mitochondrial DNA encodes only a small fraction (about 1%) of total cellular proteins, not all mitochondrial proteins.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBecause mitochondrial proteins are encoded by both nuclear and mitochondrial DNA, mitochondrial disorders can have different inheritance patterns: maternal (mitochondrial DNA), X-linked, or autosomal (nuclear DNA).\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Mitochondria are derived from prokaryotes and contain their own DNA that encodes about 1% of total cellular protein and 20% of proteins involved in oxidative phosphorylation.","Mitochondrial DNA is maternally inherited because the ovum contributes most cytoplasmic organelles to the zygote.","Most mitochondrial proteins are encoded by nuclear DNA, with only a small fraction encoded by mitochondrial DNA."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 1, The Cell as a Unit of Health and Disease;  p. 15-16"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78277"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20727"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78277","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/78277"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-27T22:55:19+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-27T22:56:23+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13603"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"95401"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11578","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11578"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"The cell as a unit of health and disease","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":0,"createdAt":"2025-02-26T15:05:04+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-26T15:05:04+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGrou